Think of it this way: reflections preserve area (think of reflecting a square – it's still the same size), but they flip the orientation. This "flipping" is represented by a determinant of -1.

\begin{align*}
\boxed{\det \mathbf{R} = -1}
\end{align*}

While rotations are more of a geometry topic, I can certainly help with the matrix representation!

Think of it this way: each point in the plane can be represented by a vector. Rotating that vector clockwise by 45 degrees is like applying a specific transformation to its coordinates. This transformation is captured by a matrix.

The matrix for a clockwise rotation by 45 degrees is:

$$
\boxed{\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} & \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\
-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} & \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}
\end{bmatrix}}
$$ 

